84. Largest Rectangle in Histogram

Given an array of integers heights representing the histogram's bar height where the width of each bar is 1, return the area of the largest rectangle in the histogram.

class Solution {
  public int largestRectangleArea(int[] heights) {   // function to calculate largest rectangle

    int max = 0;   // variable to store maximum area

    for (int i = 0; i < heights.length; i++)   // outer loop: starting index
    {
        int minH = Integer.MAX_VALUE;   // initialize minimum height

        for (int j = 1; j < heights.length; i++)   //  inner loop (mistake: j start & increment)
        {
            minH = Math.min(minH, heights[j]);   // update minimum height in range

            max = Math.max(max, (j - i + 1) * minH);   // calculate area and update max
        }
    }

    return max;   // return maximum area
    }
}


import java.util.*; // Import required for Stack and Arrays

class Solution {
    public int largestRectangleArea(int[] heights) {

        int n = heights.length; // store size of array

        int[] nsei = new int[n]; // Next Smaller Element Index (right side)
        int[] psei = new int[n]; // Previous Smaller Element Index (left side)

        Arrays.fill(nsei, n);   // default: no smaller element on right → set to n
        Arrays.fill(psei, -1);  // default: no smaller element on left → set to -1

        Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>(); // stack to store indices

        // 🔹 Step 1: Find Next Smaller Element (NSE)
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            // while stack not empty AND current height is smaller than stack top height
            while (!st.isEmpty() && heights[i] < heights[st.peek()]) {

                int idx = st.pop();   // pop index
                nsei[idx] = i;        // update next smaller index for popped element
            }

            st.push(i); // push current index into stack
        }

        st.clear(); // clear stack to reuse it

        // 🔹 Step 2: Find Previous Smaller Element (PSE)
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {

            // while stack not empty AND current height is smaller
            while (!st.isEmpty() && heights[i] < heights[st.peek()]) {

                int idx = st.pop();   // pop index
                psei[idx] = i;        // update previous smaller index
            }

            st.push(i); // push current index
        }

        int max = 0; // variable to store maximum area

        // 🔹 Step 3: Calculate max area
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int width = nsei[i] - psei[i] - 1; // width of rectangle
            int area = heights[i] * width;     // area using current height

            max = Math.max(max, area); // update max area
        }

        return max; // return final answer
    }
}


| Approach          | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
| ----------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |
| ❌ Brute Force     | O(n³)           | O(1)             |
| ✅ Optimal (Stack) | O(n)            | O(n)             |

